Definition B.17. Let $F$ be a frame. Then we say that two surjective frame morphisms $g:F\to G$ and $h:F\to H$ are equivalent if and only if there is an isomorphism $k:G\to H$ such that $k\circ g=h$. We denote the equivalence class of a surjection $g$ by $[g]_{E}$, and the set of equivalence classes of surjective frame morphisms with domain $F$ by $\mathcal{E}(F)$. The latter can be ordered in a following way. If $g,h\in\mathcal{E}(F)$, we say that $[g]_{E}\leq[h]_{E}$ if there is a frame morphism $k$ such that $h=k\circ g$.
Definition A.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a C*-algebra with unit $1_{\mathcal{A}}$. We denote the set of its commutative C*-subalgebras containing $1_{\mathcal{A}}$ by $\mathcal{C}(\mathcal{A})$.
Definition 3.6. Let $K$ be a Grothendieck topology of a subset $X$ of a poset $\mathbf{P}$. Then we define the extension $J_{K}$ of $K$ on $\mathbf{P}$ by $J_{K}(p)=\{S\in\mathcal{D}({\downarrow\,}p):S\cap\bar{}{\downarrow\,}x\in K(x)% \ \forall x\in\bar{}{\downarrow\,}p\}.$
Definition 2.15. For $n\geq 1$, the interchange graph $F(n)$ is the directed graph with vertex set $VF(n)$ and edge set $EF(n)$. The symmetric group $S_{n}$ acts freely on $VF(n)$ by permutation of the positions of the indeterminates in the monomials. Since the edges in $EF(n)$ represent relations $m\equiv m^{\prime}$ between monomials in $VF(n)$, the action of $S_{n}$ extends compatibly to the graph $F(n)$. Hence this action induces a quotient graph $G(n)$ and a covering projection $p\colon F(n)\to G(n)$.
Definition 2.4. The small Schröder number $t(n)$ is the number of distinct ways to insert balanced parentheses into a sequence of $n$ arguments such that each pair of parentheses encloses two or more arguments or parenthesized subsequences; parentheses enclosing a single argument are not allowed. More formally, as in Stanley [22, p. 345], we may recursively define bracketings as follows: the symbol $x$ is a bracketing, and for $k\geq 2$ the symbol $(w_{1}\cdots w_{k})$ is a bracketing where each $w_{i}$ is a bracketing for $1\leq i\leq k$. Then $t(n)$ is the number of distinct bracketings which contain exactly $n$ occurrences of $x$.
Definition 2.11. With the convention of Remark 2.10, every association type $t$ of degree $n\geq 2$ can be written uniquely as either $t=t^{\prime}\circ t^{\prime\prime}$ or $t=t^{\prime}\bullet t^{\prime\prime}$. This permits us to define recursively a total order on association types. The basis is the unique association type in degree 1. Let $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ be association types of degrees $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ respectively; then $t_{1}$ precedes $t_{2}$ (denoted $t_{1}\prec t_{2}$) if and only if: (i) $n_{1}<n_{2}$: first we look at the number of leaves; or (ii) $n_{1}=n_{2}$ and $t_{1}=t^{\prime}_{1}\circ t^{\prime\prime}_{1}$ and $t_{2}=t^{\prime}_{2}\bullet t^{\prime\prime}_{2}$: next we look at the operation at the root with the convention that $\circ$ precedes $\bullet$; or (iii) $n_{1}=n_{2}$ and $t_{1}=t^{\prime}_{1}\ast t^{\prime\prime}_{1}$ and $t_{2}=t^{\prime}_{2}\ast t^{\prime\prime}_{2}$ with the same operation $\ast$, and either $t^{\prime}_{1}\prec t^{\prime}_{2}$, or $t^{\prime}_{1}=t^{\prime}_{2}$ and $t^{\prime\prime}_{1}\prec t^{\prime\prime}_{2}$: finally we use recursion on the unique factorization of each association type into two factors.
Definition 2.5. The large Schröder number $T(n)$ is the number of paths in the $xy$-plane from the origin $(0,0)$ to the point $(n,n)$ that do not rise above the line $y=x$ and which use only steps north $(0,1)$, east $(1,0)$, or northeast $(1,1)$.
Definition 2.14. Each relation $R\in C(n)$, written as $m_{i}\equiv m_{j}$, gives rise to two directed edges between the multilinear monomials $m_{i},m_{j}\in VF(n)$: $m_{i}\xrightarrow{\quad e_{R}\quad}m_{j},\qquad\qquad m_{i}\xleftarrow{\quad e% ^{\prime}_{R}\quad}m_{j}.$ The set $EF(n)$ of edges of the graph $F(n)$ consists of all these edges: $EF(n)=\bigcup_{R\in C(n)}\{\,e_{R},\,e^{\prime}_{R}\,\}.$ More precisely, we write $\sigma_{i},\sigma_{j}$ for the underlying permutations of $m_{i},m_{j}$ and represent the directed edges obtained from $R$ as follows; the permutation labelling one edge is the inverse of the permutation labelling the other: $\begin{array}[]{c}\leavevmode\hbox to117.66pt{\vbox to71.35pt{\pgfpicture% \makeatletter\hbox to 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}% \pgfsys@invoke{ }\nullfont\hbox to 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{13.948975pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{13.948975pt}{7.70380% 6pt}{7.703806pt}{13.948975pt}{0.0pt}{13.948975pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-7.703806pt}{% 13.948975pt}{-13.948975pt}{7.703806pt}{-13.948975pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-13% .948975pt}{-7.703806pt}{-7.703806pt}{-13.948975pt}{0.0pt}{-13.948975pt}% \pgfsys@curveto{7.703806pt}{-13.948975pt}{13.948975pt}{-7.703806pt}{13.948975% pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke% \pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-7.019893pt}{-2.351964pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{\large{$m_{i}$}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfs