Definition 2.3. The forgetful map $p\colon VF(n)\to VG(n)$ assigns to a multilinear monomial $m$ its association type $p(m)$ by ignoring the permutation of the indeterminates. As before, if we are careful, we may say that $p(m)$ is obtained from $m$ by replacing $a_{\sigma(1)},\dots,a_{\sigma(n)}$ by the identity permutation $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$.
Definition 1.1. A double semigroup is a set $S$ with two associative binary operations $\bullet,\circ$ satisfying the interchange relation for all $a,b,c,d\in S$: $(a\bullet b)\circ(c\bullet d)\equiv(a\circ c)\bullet(b\circ d).$ The symbol $\equiv$ indicates that the equation holds for all values of the variables.
Definition 2.2. We write $VF(n)$ for the set of multilinear monomials in degree $n$; they are obtained from the association types by inserting the indeterminates $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}$ from left to right and applying all permutations $\sigma\in S_{n}$. In this case (and only this case) it does not matter whether we apply $\sigma$ to the positions or to the subscripts of the indeterminates, so after applying $\sigma$ the underlying indeterminates from left to right are $a_{\sigma(1)},\dots,a_{\sigma(n)}$.
Definition 3.1. The circuit rank (or cyclomatic number) of a graph $G$ is the minimum number $r$ of edges which must be removed to eliminate all of the cycles, thus resulting in a forest (a disjoint union of trees).
Definition 2.1. We write $VG(n)$ for the set of association types in degree $n$: the possible placements of balanced parentheses and binary operation symbols in a monomial of degree $n$ with two associative operations $\{\circ,\bullet\}$.
Definition 5.1. (Loday and Vallette [14, §13.10.4]) An interchange algebra is a vector space $A$ over a field $\mathbb{F}$ with two bilinear products $\circ,\bullet\colon A\times A\to A$ which are associative and satisfy the interchange relation ($\boxplus$ ‣ 1.1). The corresponding symmetric operad is the interchange operad; we denote it by $\mathsf{INT}$.
Definition 2.18. A commutativity property in degree $n$ for double semigroups corresponds to a directed cycle $C$ in the quotient graph $G(n)$ for which the product of the permutations along the edges is not the identity. In this case we call $C$ a nontrivial cycle. A nontrivial cycle is a closed path in $G(n)$ for which some (and hence any) lifting to $F(n)$ is not closed. If a nontrivial cycle passes through association type $t$, then we may regard $t$ as the first and last vertex of the cycle, and obtain a commutativity property of the form $m\equiv m^{\prime}$, where both monomials have association type $t$ but different permutations of the indeterminates.
Definition 2.12. The set $C(n)$ of consequences in degree $n$ of the interchange relation is defined inductively starting with $C(n)=\emptyset$ for $1\leq n\leq 3$ and $C(4)=\{m_{1}\equiv m_{2}\}$ where $m_{1}\equiv m_{2}$ is the interchange relation ($\boxplus$ ‣ 1.1). For $n\geq 4$ we consider a relation $R\in C(n)$ written as $m_{1}\equiv m_{2}$ for multilinear monomials $m_{1},m_{2}\in VF(n)$. The consequences of $R$ in degree $n+1$ are defined as follows: (i) For each $i\in\{1,\dots,n\}$ and $\ast\in\{\circ,\bullet\}$ we substitute $a_{i}\ast a_{n+1}$ for $a_{i}$ in $m_{1}$ and $m_{2}$ and obtain these $2n$ relations in degree $n+1$: $m_{1}\big{|}_{a_{i}=a_{i}\ast a_{n+1}}\equiv\,m_{2}\big{|}_{a_{i}=a_{i}\ast a_% {n+1}}$ (ii) For each $\ast\in\{\circ,\bullet\}$ we right- or left-multiply $m_{1}$ and $m_{2}$ by $a_{n+1}$ and obtain these 4 relations in degree $n+1$: $m_{1}\ast a_{n+1}\,\equiv\,m_{2}\ast a_{n+1},\qquad a_{n+1}\ast m_{1}\,\equiv% \,a_{n+1}\ast m_{2}.$ We write $c(R)$ for the set of all consequences of $R$ in degree $n+1$, and define $C(n+1)=\bigcup_{R\in C(n)}c(R).$ It follows immediately from (i) and (ii) that for $n\geq 4$, every element of $C(n)$ has the form $m_{1}\equiv m_{2}$ where $m_{1}$ and $m_{2}$ are multilinear monomials of degree $n$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathsf{T}$ be a triangulated category, and $\mathsf{\Sigma}$ its suspension functor; soon we will focus on the derived category of an abelian category. Let $\mathsf{C}$ be a subcategory (always assumed to be full) of $\mathsf{T}$. We write $\operatorname{add}(\mathsf{C})$ for the smallest subcategory of $\mathsf{T}$ containing $\mathsf{C}$ and closed under finite direct sums, retracts, and shifts. Given a subcategory $\mathsf{D}$ of $\mathsf{T}$, the subcategory consisting of objects $E$ that appear in exact triangles of the form $C\to E\to D\to\mathsf{\Sigma}C\quad\text{with $C\in\mathsf{C}$ and $D\in% \mathsf{D}$},$ is denoted $\mathsf{C}\ast\mathsf{D}$. It is convenient to introduce also the following notation: $\mathsf{C}{\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{D}:=\operatorname{add}(\mathsf{C}\ast\mathsf{D% })\,.$ It is a consequence of the octahedral axiom that there are equalities $(\mathsf{B}\ast\mathsf{C})\ast\mathsf{D}=\mathsf{B}\ast(\mathsf{C}\ast\mathsf{% D})\text{ and }(\mathsf{B}{\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{C}){\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{D}=% \mathsf{B}{\,\diamond\,}(\mathsf{C}{\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{D})\,.$ In particular, we may well denote them $\mathsf{B}\ast\mathsf{C}\ast\mathsf{D}$ and $\mathsf{B}{\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{C}{\,\diamond\,}\mathsf{D}$, respectively.
Definition 2.5. For $r\in R$, let $\mathsf{T}_{r}$ denote the subcategory of $\mathsf{T}$ consisting of complexes $X$ such that the multiplication morphism $X\xrightarrow{r}X$ is zero in $\mathsf{T}$; in other words, $r$ is in the kernel of the natural map $R\to\operatorname{End}_{\mathsf{T}}(X)$.
Definition 2.2. An additive category $\mathsf{A}$ is said to be $R$-linear if for each $A$ in $\mathsf{A}$ there are homomorphisms of rings $\eta_{A}\colon R\to\operatorname{End}_{\mathsf{A}}(A)$ with the property that the action of $R$ on $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{A}}(A,B)$ induced by $\eta_{A}$ and $\eta_{B}$ coincide, for all $A,B$ in $\mathsf{A}$. Said otherwise, $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{A}}(A,B)$ is an $R$-module and this structure is compatible with compositions in $\mathsf{A}$.
Definition 2.9. For an element $r\in R$ and an integer $n\geq 0$ we consider the following four conditions on the triangulated category $\mathsf{T}:=\mathsf{D}^{\mathsf{b}}(\mathsf{A})$. $\displaystyle\mathrm{D}_{r,n}\quad\mathsf{T}=\mathsf{T}_{r}{\,\diamond\,}% \mathsf{P}_{n}\,,\quad\text{and}$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{E}_{r,n}\quad\ r\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathsf{A}}^{n}(% \mathsf{A},\mathsf{A})=0\,,$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{D}^{\prime}_{r,n}\quad\mathsf{T}=\mathsf{P}_{n}{\,% \diamond\,}\mathsf{T}_{r}\,,\quad\text{and}$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{G}_{r,n}\quad r\mathcal{G}^{n}=0\,.$
Definition 2.2. The pair $(\mathcal{P},\Pi)$ is called the Poisson boundary of $(\mathcal{C},\mu)$. We say that the Poisson boundary is trivial if $\Pi\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{P}$ is an equivalence of categories, or in other words, for all objects $U$ and $V$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the only bounded $P_{\mu}$-harmonic natural transformations $\iota\otimes U\to\iota\otimes V$ are the transformations of the form $\eta=(\iota_{X}\otimes T)_{X}$ for $T\in\mathcal{C}(U,V)$.
Definition 6.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a C${}^{*}$-tensor category and $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{A}$ be a unitary tensor functor into a C${}^{*}$-tensor category $\mathcal{A}$ with possibly nonsimple unit. A right invariant mean for $F$ is a collection $m=(m_{U,V})_{U,V}$ of linear maps $m_{U,V}\colon\hat{\mathcal{C}}(U,V)\to\mathcal{A}(F(U),F(V))$ that are natural in $U$ and $V$ and satisfy the following properties: (i) the maps $m_{U}=m_{U,U}\colon\hat{\mathcal{C}}(U)\to\mathcal{A}\left(F(U)\right)$ are unital and positive; (ii) for any $\eta\in\hat{\mathcal{C}}(U,V)$ and any object $Y$ in $\mathcal{C}$ we have $m_{U\otimes Y,V\otimes Y}(\eta\otimes\iota_{Y})=F_{2}(m_{U,V}(\eta)\otimes% \iota_{F(Y)});$ (iii) for any $\eta\in\hat{\mathcal{C}}(U,V)$ and any object $Y$ in $\mathcal{C}$ we have $m_{Y\otimes U,Y\otimes V}(\iota_{Y}\otimes\eta)=F_{2}(\iota_{F(Y)}\otimes m_{U% ,V}(\eta)).$ If a right invariant mean for $F$ exists, we say that $F$ is amenable.
Definition 5.3.2. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be equipped with a hermitian structure. A type $(1,0)$ connective structure on $\mathcal{G}$ is compatible with the hermitian structure if for each object $P$ of $\mathcal{G}$ there is an isomorphism of torsors $\displaystyle\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ $\displaystyle r$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto\nabla_{r}$ such that for a positive function $\rho$ on $U$ $r\cdot\rho\longmapsto\nabla_{r}+\partial\log\rho\,.$ (In other words, $\nabla_{r\cdot\rho}=\nabla_{r}+\partial\log\rho\,.$)
Definition 5.5.4. Let $\mathsf{G}$ be a $\mathcal{O}_{X}^{\times}$-$2$-gerbe on $X$. 1. A type $(1,0)$ concept of connectivity on $\mathsf{G}$ is the assignment of a $F^{1}\!\underline{\mathnormal{A}}_{U}^{1}$-gerbe $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ to each object $P$ in $\mathsf{G}_{U}$. This assignment will have to satisfy properties analogous to those of definition 5.5.1. Of course, in the last condition, the map (5.17) will have to be replaced by $a\mapsto d\log a\,.$ 2. A type $(1,0)$ concept of connectivity is compatible with a hermitian structure if for each object $P$ of $\mathsf{G}_{U}$ there is an equivalence of gerbes $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})\longrightarrow\underline{\operatorname{Co% }}({P})$ satisfying the obvious compatibility conditions with the operations of $\mathsf{G}_{U}$ and the restrictions.
Definition 5.2.1. A hermitian structure on $\mathcal{G}$ consists of the following data: 1. For each object $P$ in $\mathcal{G}_{U}$, is assigned a $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-torsor $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ (a $\mathbb{R}_{+}$-principal bundle). The assignment must be compatible with the restriction functors $i^{*}\colon\mathcal{G}_{U}\to\mathcal{G}_{V}$ arising from $i\colon V\hookrightarrow U$ in the cover $\mathfrak{U}_{X}$ of $X$. 2. For each morphism $f\colon P\to Q$ in $\mathcal{G}_{U}$ a corresponding morphism $f_{*}\colon\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})\to\underline{\operatorname{% herm}}({Q})$ of $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-torsors.1A $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-torsor will in general be automatically trivializable. However, in this context it is convenient to “forget” the actual trivializing map. This map must be compatible with compositions of morphisms in $\mathcal{G}_{U}$ and with the restriction functors. For an object $P$ of $\mathcal{G}_{U}$, an automorphism $\varphi\in\underline{\operatorname{Aut}}(P)$ is identified with a section of $\mathcal{O}_{X}^{\times}$ over $U$. We then require that $\displaystyle\varphi_{*}\colon\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ $\displaystyle\overset{\simeq}{\longrightarrow}\underline{\operatorname{herm}}(% {P})$ (5.5) $\displaystyle h$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto h\cdot\left\lvert\varphi\right\rvert^{2}$ where the latter is the $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-action on the torsor $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$.
Definition 5.7.1. We say that $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({\cdot})^{\mathit{an}}$ and $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({\cdot})^{\mathit{h}}$ are compatible if for any object $P$ of $\mathcal{G}_{U}$, $U\subset X$, there is an isomorphism of torsors $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})^{\mathit{an}}\cong\underline{\operatorname{% Co}}({P})^{\mathit{h}}$ (after lambda-extension of $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})^{\mathit{an}}$ from $\underline{\mathnormal{\Omega}}_{U}^{1}$ to $\underline{\mathnormal{A}}_{U}^{1,0}$.)
Definition 5.3.1. A type $(1,0)$ connective structure on $\mathcal{G}$ is the assignment to each object $P$ of $\mathcal{G}_{U}$ of a $F^{1}\!\underline{\mathnormal{A}}_{U}^{1}$-torsor $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ compatible with restriction functors and morphisms of objects. In particular, for $\varphi\in\underline{\operatorname{Aut}}(P)$, we require that $\displaystyle\varphi_{*}\colon\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ $\displaystyle\overset{\simeq}{\longrightarrow}\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ (5.10) $\displaystyle\nabla$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto\nabla+d\log\varphi$ where $\nabla$ is a section of $\underline{\operatorname{Co}}({P})$ over $U$.2Note that $d\log\varphi$ is holomorphic, hence of type $(1,0)$.
Definition 3.2.1. The hypercohomology groups $H^{p}_{\mathcal{D}_{\smash[b]{\mathit{h.h.}}}}(X,l)\>\overset{\mathrm{def}}{=}% \>\mathbf{H}^{p}(X,C(l))$ are the Hermitian holomorphic Deligne cohomology groups.
Definition 4.3.1. Define the map $\begin{split}\displaystyle\bigl{(}\mathbb{Z}(1)_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}\bigr{)}% \otimes\bigl{(}\mathbb{Z}(1)_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}\bigr{)}&\displaystyle% \longrightarrow\bigl{(}\mathbb{Z}(2)_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}\xrightarrow{-\pi_{1% }}\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{X}^{0}(1)\bigr{)}\\ &\displaystyle\overset{\simeq}{\longrightarrow}2\pi\smash{\sqrt{-1}}\otimes% \bigl{(}\mathbb{Z}(1)_{X}\to\mathcal{O}_{X}\xrightarrow{-\pi_{0}}\underline{% \mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{X}^{0}\bigr{)}\end{split}$ by using (4.8) in place of the map $\mathcal{O}_{X}\otimes\mathcal{O}_{X}\to\underline{\mathnormal{\Omega}}_{X}^{1% }\,,$ $f\otimes g\mapsto fdg\,,$ in (2.4).
Definition 5.5.1. A hermitian structure on a $\mathcal{O}_{X}^{\times}$-$2$-gerbe $\mathsf{G}$ over $X$ consists of the following data. 1. To each object $P$ in the fiber $2$-category $\mathsf{G}_{U}$ over $U\subset X$ we assign a $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-gerbe $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ over $U$. (As before, $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$ is the sheaf of real positive functions on $U$.) 2. This assignment must be compatible with the inverse image $2$-functors $i^{*}\colon\mathsf{G}_{U}\to\mathsf{G}_{V}\,,$ natural transformations $\varphi_{i,j}\colon j^{*}i^{*}\Rightarrow(ij)^{*}$ and modifications $\alpha_{i,j,k}\colon\varphi_{ij,k}\circ(h^{*}*\varphi_{i,j})\Rrightarrow% \varphi_{i,jk}\circ(\varphi_{j,k}*i^{*})$ arising from the inclusions $i\colon V\hookrightarrow U,$ $j\colon W\hookrightarrow V,$ and $k\colon Z\hookrightarrow W,$ in the cover $\mathfrak{U}_{X}$. 3. For each $1$-arrow $f\colon P\to Q$ in $\mathsf{G}_{U}$ a corresponding equivalence $f_{*}\colon\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})\to\underline{\operatorname{% herm}}({Q})$ of $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-gerbes. For each $2$-arrow $\alpha\colon f\Rightarrow f^{\prime}$ a corresponding natural transformation $\alpha_{*}\colon f_{*}\Rightarrow f^{\prime}_{*}$ between equivalences. We ask that this correspondence be compatible with compositions of $1$- and $2$-arrows. Namely, for $1$-arrows $f,f^{\prime}\colon P\to Q$ and $g,g^{\prime}\colon Q\to R$ and for $2$-arrows $\alpha\colon f\Rightarrow f^{\prime}$ and $\beta\colon g\Rightarrow g^{\prime}$ in $\mathsf{G}_{U}$, which we compose as $\beta*\alpha\colon g\circ f\Rightarrow g^{\prime}\circ f^{\prime},$ we find a diagram of natural transformations $\xymatrix@!C{g_{*}\circ f_{*}\ar@{=>}[d]_{\beta_{*}*\alpha_{*}}\ar@{=>}[r]^{% \varepsilon(f,g)}&(g\circ f)_{*}\ar@{=>}[d]^{(\beta*\alpha)_{*}}\\ g^{\prime}_{*}\circ f^{\prime}_{*}\ar@{=>}[r]_{-}{\varepsilon(f^{\prime},g^{% \prime})}&(g^{\prime}\circ f^{\prime})_{*}}$ of equivalences between the $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$-gerbes $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ and $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({R})$ on $U\subset X.$ 4. From the axioms, the group of automorphisms of a $1$-arrow $f\colon P\to Q$ in $\mathsf{G}_{U}$ is identified with $\mathcal{O}_{U}^{\times}$. It follows that such an automorphism $\alpha$ (that is, a $2$-arrow from $f$ to itself) can be identified with a section $a\in\mathcal{O}_{U}^{\times}$. We then require that the induced natural isomorphism $\alpha_{*}\colon f_{*}\Longrightarrow f_{*}\,,\quad\text{where}\;f_{*}\colon% \underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})\longrightarrow\underline{\operatorname{% herm}}({Q})$ be identified with a section of $\underline{\mathnormal{\mathcal{E}}}_{U,+}^{0}$ via the map $a\longmapsto\left\lvert a\right\rvert^{2}$ and an appropriate labeling of $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({P})$ and $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({Q})$ by objects $r$ and $s$, respectively. In more detail, given an arrow $f_{*}(r)\to s$ in $\underline{\operatorname{herm}}({Q})$, the action of $\alpha$ via $\alpha_{*}$ will amount to an automorphism of $s$. We require that it be $\left\lvert a\right\rvert^{2}$.
Definition 3.1. The dimension of ${\mathcal{T}}$, denoted by $\dim{\mathcal{T}}$, is the minimal integer $d\geq 0$ such that there is $M$ in ${\mathcal{T}}$ with ${\mathcal{T}}=\langle M\rangle_{d+1}$. We define the dimension to be $\infty$ when there is no such $M$.
Definition. A normed set is a pair $(S,f)$, where $S$ is a set and $f$ a function from $S$ to $[0,\infty)$. The function $f$ is called the norm function.
Definition. Given two normed sets $(S,f)$ and $(T,g)$, a function $\phi:S\to T$ is bounded if there is $M\geq 0$ such that for all $s\in S$, $g\left(\phi(s)\right)\leq Mf(s)$. Let $\operatorname{crh}(\phi):=\inf\left\{M\in[0,\infty):g\left(\phi(s)\right)\leq Mf% (s)\forall s\in S\right\},$ the bound constant of $\phi$. If $\operatorname{crh}(\phi)\leq 1$, $\phi$ is contractive.
Definition 1.4. Let $A$ be an NCPA. A quasi-Poisson $A$-module $M$ is a an $A$-$A$-bimodule $M$ together with a $\mathbb{K}$-bilinear map $\{-,-\}_{*}\colon A\times M\longrightarrow M,$ which satisfies $\displaystyle\{a,b\cdot m\}_{*}=\{a,b\}\cdot m+b\cdot\{a,m\}_{*},$ $\displaystyle\{a,m\cdot b\}_{*}=m\cdot\{a,b\}+\{a,m\}_{*}\cdot b,$ $\displaystyle\{\{a,b\},m\}_{*}=\{a,\{b,m\}_{*}\}_{*}-\{b,\{a,m\}_{*}\}_{*}$ for all $a,b\in A$ and $m\in M$, and $a\cdot m$ and $m\cdot a$ denote the left and right $A$-action on $M$ respectively. Note that the last condition is just equivalent to say that $M$ is a Lie module over $A$. If moreover, $\displaystyle\{ab,m\}_{*}=a\cdot\{b,m\}_{*}+\{a,m\}_{*}\cdot b$ holds for all $a,b\in A$ and $m\in M$, then $M$ is called a Poisson $A$-module. A homomorphism of quasi-Poisson $A$-modules (resp. Poisson modules) is a $\mathbb{K}$-linear map $f\colon M\rightarrow N$ such that $\displaystyle f(a\cdot m)=a\cdot f(m),\ \ f(m\cdot a)=f(m)\cdot a,$ $\displaystyle f(\{a,m\}_{*})=\{a,f(m)\}_{*}$ hold for all $a\in A$ and $m\in M$. We denote the category of quasi-Poisson $A$-modules (resp. Poisson modules) by ${\operatorname{Q}(A)}$ (resp. ${\operatorname{P}(A)}$).
Definition 1.1. A non-commutative Poisson algebra (NCPA) over $\mathbb{K}$ is a triple $A=(A,{\scriptscriptstyle\bullet},\{-,-\})$, where $A$ is a $\mathbb{K}$-space, $(A,{\scriptscriptstyle\bullet})$ is an associative algebra and $(A,\{-,-\})$ is a Lie algebra, such that the Leibniz rule $\{ab,c\}=a\{b,c\}+\{a,c\}b$ holds for all $a,b,c\in A$, here we write $a{\scriptscriptstyle\bullet}b$ as $ab$ for brevity. The operator ${\scriptscriptstyle\bullet}$ is called the multiplication and $\{-,-\}$ the Poisson bracket of $A$.
Definition 2.4. Let $A=(A,{\scriptscriptstyle\bullet},\{-,-\})$ be an NCPA. The smash product $A^{e}\#\mathcal{U}(A)$ is called the quasi-Poisson enveloping algebra of $A$ and denoted by $\mathcal{Q}(A)$. The Poisson enveloping algebra of $A$, denoted by $\mathcal{P}(A)$, is defined to be the quotient algebra $\mathcal{Q}(A)/J$, here $J$ is the ideal of $\mathcal{Q}(A)$ generated by $\{1_{A}\otimes 1_{A^{op}}\#(a{\scriptscriptstyle\bullet}b)-a\otimes 1_{A^{op}}% \#b-1_{A}\otimes b\#a|\ a,b\in A\}.$
Definition 2.5. [26] A Reedy fibrant simplicial space $W$ is a Segal space if the Segal maps are weak equivalences of simplicial sets.
Definition 5.1. [8] Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be categories enriched in $\Theta_{n-1}Sp$. An enriched functor $f\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ is a weak equivalence if (1) $\text{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(x,y)\rightarrow\text{Map}_{\mathcal{D}}(fx,fy)$ is a weak equivalence in $\Theta_{n-1}Sp$ for any objects $x,y$, and (2) $\pi_{0}\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\pi_{0}\mathcal{D}$ is an equivalence of categories, where $\pi_{0}\mathcal{C}$ has the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ and $\text{Hom}_{\pi_{0}\mathcal{C}}(x,y)=\text{Hom}_{\text{Ho}(\Theta_{n-1}Sp)}(1,% \text{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(x,y))$.
Definition 7.3. For $n\geq 1$, define a weak $n$-category $Cob_{n}(n)$ to have objects 0-dimensional closed framed 0-dimensional manifolds, 1-morphisms framed cobordisms between them, 2-morphisms framed cobordisms between the cobordisms, up to $n$-morphisms which are diffeomorphism classes of framed cobordisms of dimension $n$.
Definition 3.4. A Reedy fibrant $n$-fold simplicial space is an $n$-fold Segal space if • each Segal map $X_{k}\rightarrow\underbrace{X_{1}\times_{X_{0}}\cdots\times_{X_{0}}X_{1}}_{k}$ is a weak equivalence of $(n-1)$-fold Segal spaces for each $k\geq 2$, • $X_{k}$ is an $(n-1)$-fold Segal space for each $k\geq 0$, and • the $(n-1)$-fold Segal space $X_{0}$ is essentially constant.
Definition 7.1. For $n\geq 1$, denote by $Cob(n)$ the category with objects closed framed $(n-1)$-dimensional manifolds and morphisms the diffeomorphism classes of framed cobordisms between them.
Definition 7.6. [23, 2.2] Let $V$ be a finite-dimensional vector space. Define an $n$-fold simplicial space $PBord_{n}^{fr,V}$ by $(PBord_{n}^{fr,V})_{k_{1},\ldots,k_{n}}=\{(M,\{t_{0}^{1}\leq\cdots,\leq t^{1}_% {k_{1}}\},\ldots,\{t_{0}^{1}\leq\cdots,t_{k_{n}}^{n}\})\}$ where: • $M$ is a closed $n$-dimensional framed submanifold of $V\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$ such that the projection $M\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$ is proper, • for every $S\subseteq\{1,\ldots,n\}$ and every $\{0\leq j_{i}\leq k_{i}\}_{i\in S}$, the composite map $M\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{S}$ does not have $(t_{j_{i}})_{i\in S}$ as a critical value, and • the map $M\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{\{i+1,\ldots,n\}}$ is submersive at every $x\in M$ whose image in $\mathbb{R}^{\{i\}}$ belongs to the set $\{t_{i_{0}},\ldots,t_{i_{k}}\}$. As $V$ ranges over all finite-dimensional subspaces of $\mathbb{R}^{\infty}$, let $PBord_{n}^{fr}=\text{colim}_{V}PBord^{fr,V}_{n}.$
Definition 4.2. [3] A quasi-$n$-category is a functor $\Theta_{n}^{op}\rightarrow\mathcal{S}ets$ satisfying appropriate inner horn-filling conditions.
Definition 3.1. An $n$-fold simplicial space is a functor $X\colon({\bf\Delta}^{op})^{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{SS}ets$.
Definition 7.2. For a field $k$, a topological quantum field theory of dimension $n$ is a symmetric monoidal functor $Z\colon Cob(n)\rightarrow Vect(k)$, where $Vect(k)$ is the category of vector spaces equipped with the usual tensor product.
Definition 3.2. An $n$-fold simplicial space $X\colon{\bf\Delta}^{op}\rightarrow\mathcal{SS}ets^{({\bf\Delta}^{op})^{n-1}}_{disc}$ is a Segal $n$-precategory if $X_{0}$ is discrete. It is a Segal $n$-category if, in addition, the Segal maps $X_{k}\rightarrow\underbrace{X_{1}\times_{X_{0}}\cdots\times_{X_{0}}X_{1}}_{k}$ are weak equivalences of Segal $(n-1)$-categories for $n\geq 2$.
Definition 7.8. Define $Bord_{n}^{fr}$ to be the completion of $PBord_{n}^{fr}$.
Definition 2.2. [17] A simplicial space $X$ is a Segal precategory if $X_{0}$ is discrete. It is a Segal category if, in addition, the Segal maps are weak equivalences of simplicial sets.
Definition 2.6. [26] A Segal space is complete if the map $s_{0}\colon W_{0}\rightarrow W_{h}$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets.
Definition 5.3. [8] A Segal precategory object in $\Theta_{n-1}Sp$ is a functor $X\colon{\bf\Delta}^{op}\rightarrow\Theta_{n-1}Sp$ such that the functor $X_{0}\colon\Theta_{n-1}^{op}\rightarrow\mathcal{SS}ets$ is discrete. It is a Segal category object if the Segal maps are weak equivalences in $\Theta_{n-1}Sp$.
